Suddenly all that matters in those intervening years was transformers!

This keynote was very much an evolution of that theme. Yes, the surface lev=
el understanding of Nvidia=E2=80=99s transformation from a gaming company t=
o an AI company is true, but maybe the most precise description is that Nvi=
dia is a transformer company. To the point above, the 50-series is better t=
han the 40-series at traditional graphics rendering, but the real standout =
feature =E2=80=94 and the clear future of graphics =E2=80=94 is leveraging =
transformers.

Cosmos and Omniverse
--------------------

The other big announcement during the keynote was the Cosmos world foundati=
on model. From the Nvidia Press Release ( https://nvidianews.nvidia.com/new=
s/nvidia-launches-cosmos-world-foundation-model-platform-to-accelerate-phys=
ical-ai-development ) :

NVIDIA today announced NVIDIA Cosmos, a platform comprising state-of-the-ar=
t generative world foundation models, advanced tokenizers, guardrails and a=
n accelerated video processing pipeline built to advance the development of=
 physical AI systems such as autonomous vehicles (AVs) and robots.

Physical AI models are costly to develop, and require vast amounts of real-=
world data and testing. Cosmos world foundation models, or WFMs, offer deve=
lopers an easy way to generate massive amounts of photoreal, physics-based =
synthetic data to train and evaluate their existing models. Developers can =
also build custom models by fine-tuning Cosmos WFMs.

What was interesting to me was Huang=E2=80=99s description of how Cosmos wo=
rks with Omniverse, the digital twin/metaverse product the company launched=
 in 2021. Here=E2=80=99s Huang:

( https://videopress.com/embed/YyDqn53h?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

The magic happens when you connect Cosmos to Omniverse, and the reason fund=
amentally is this: Omniverse is a physics-grounded, not physically-grounded=
, but physics-grounded. It=E2=80=99s algorithmic physics, principle physics=
 simulation grounded system. It=E2=80=99s a simulator. When you connect tha=
t to Cosmos, it provides the grounding, the ground truth, that can control =
and condition the Cosmos generation. As a result, what comes out of Cosmos,=
 is grounded on truth. This is exactly the same idea as connecting a large =
language model to a RAG, to a retrieval augmented generation system. You wa=
nt to ground the AI generation on ground truth, and so the combination of t=
he two gives you a physically-simulated, a physically-grounded, multiverse =
generator, and the application and the use cases are really quite exciting.=
 And of course for robotics, for industrial applications, it is very, very =
clear.

This Cosmos plus Omniverse represents the third computer that=E2=80=99s nec=
essary for building robotics systems. Every robotics company will ultimatel=
y have to build three computers: the robotics system could be a factory, it=
 could be a car, it could be a robot; you need three fundamental computers.=
 One computer of course to train the AI; we call it the DGX computer to tra=
in the AI. Another, of course, when you=E2=80=99re done, to deploy the AI, =
we call that AGX. That=E2=80=99s inside the car, the robot, or in an AMR, o=
r in a stadium, or whatever it is, these computers are at the edge and they=
=E2=80=99re autonomous. But to connect the two you need a digital twin, and=
 these are all the simulations. The digital twin is where the AI that has b=
een trained goes to practice, to be refined, to do synthetic data generatio=
n, reinforcement-AI feedback, such and such, and so it=E2=80=99s the digita=
l twin of the AI. These three computers are going to be working interactive=
ly. Nvidia=E2=80=99s strategy for the industrial world, and we=E2=80=99ve b=
een talking about this for some time, is this three computer system. Instea=
d of a Three Body Problem, we have a three computer solution. It=E2=80=99s =
the Nvidia robotics.

Huang then gave three examples: warehouse automation, cars, and humanoid ro=
bots. In each case the idea was that you could develop a relatively limited=
 amount of original data, like multi-sensory car data or robotic movements,=
 and then use that data to generate massively more data that you could then=
 use to train new models to operate the real-world devices. In other words =
=E2=80=94 and in keeping with the theme of this Update =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=
=99s a bet on transformers, which need massive amounts of data to train on.

What I=E2=80=99m really interested to know is if this was the point of the =
Omniverse all along. When I talked to Huang after the launch of Omniverse C=
loud ( https://stratechery.com/2021/nvidias-gtc-keynote-the-nvidia-stack-th=
e-omniverse/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnB=
hc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9yd=
C5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJo=
dHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIxL252aWRpYXMtZ3RjLWtleW5vdGUtdGhlLW52aWR=
pYS1zdGFjay10aGUtb21uaXZlcnNlLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNzM4ODQ3NzAyLCJpYXQiOjE3MzYyNT=
U3MDIsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZ=
mVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1l=
bnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.VioOSQ=
ihdTuofMT9d31doCHzxYZVcEOLc8USJ6kxhinyy-wE87MudL3EfVmi73tcb0ZJqd4GYJgYOaENj=
noiDeu2A5RkSfpSDVH_nuLmXPNo5OGEEmafuNo2i7ImbrP2qMWMqmkNe2rvXQk3W7ECGVMmswjY=
opHqI1xXFJhEA6HbCDmjhi5uMZdFeieYGlQQQhFZ9h7QGFyXjoUvLxnKUElMFrLTNTt2yheyP87=
UbLJYDvlhsr7yJDROayN51rSaE0qAm70SnFyn_25OC5iwz9SE-AtL8mH3tWwFj4fMB7HZdlz4Rw=
xx6t_QFNcjKj93-fw6CNN5rIJ_8WPh2W3L8A ) , nothing approaching this came up i=
n his answers; it=E2=80=99s possible I didn=E2=80=99t know enough to ask, b=
ut it=E2=80=99s also possible that the transformation I spoke of =E2=80=94 =
of Nvidia becoming the transformer company =E2=80=94 happened in the three =
years since that interview happened.

What I do think Cosmos represents, particularly in its self-driving applica=
tion, is an endorsement of Tesla=E2=80=99s self-driving approach, which is =
leaning extremely heavily into pure machine learning acting on video inputs=
 instead of high fidelity sensor data that is handled by algorithms. This i=
s where I go back to the first Huang quote above: everything is going to be=
 machine learning driven at some point; Nvidia may be the transformer compa=
ny now, but everyone will be at some point in the future.

Digits
------

From The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/2025/1/6/24337530/nvidia-ces-digi=
ts-super-computer-ai ) :

If you were looking for your own personal AI supercomputer, Nvidia has you =
covered. The chipmaker announced at CES it=E2=80=99s launching a personal A=
I supercomputer called Project Digits in May. The heart of Project Digits i=
s the new GB10 Grace Blackwell Superchip, which packs enough processing pow=
er to run sophisticated AI models while being compact enough to fit on a de=
sk and run from a standard power outlet (this kind of processing power used=
 to require much larger, more power-hungry systems). This desktop-sized sys=
tem can handle AI models with up to 200 billion parameters, and has a start=
ing price of $3,000. The product itself looks a lot like a Mac Mini.

Each Project Digits system comes equipped with 128GB of unified, coherent m=
emory (by comparison, a good laptop might have 16GB or 32GB of RAM) and up =
to 4TB of NVMe storage. For even more demanding applications, two Project D=
igits systems can be linked together to handle models with up to 405 billio=
n parameters (Meta=E2=80=99s best model, Llama 3.1, has 405 billion paramet=
ers).

Here=E2=80=99s a screen-grab:

This is the prediction I accidentally made in Dithering; I was saying how I=
 it would be useful to have a home LLM: imagine having the entirety of the =
Internet effectively available to you at all times no matter what (assuming=
 you have electricity, which solar fixes!). It=E2=80=99s pretty incredible =
when you think about it =E2=80=94 and, as always, hardware is cool!

There are three further points:

* First, while there are various discussions to be had about marginal costs=
 when it comes to reasoning, it=E2=80=99s important to keep in mind that ma=
ssive up-front data capture and generation that is transformed into models =
is in fact transferring future operational costs into one-time fixed costs.=
 Once you=E2=80=99ve captured the Internet in a model, you have the Interne=
t, even on a device that fits in your hand. Or, as in the case of DLSS, onc=
e you have trained the models you can get better graphics =E2=80=9Cfor free=
=E2=80=9D instead of hand-tuning everything.
* Second, note how the fundamental design of computers is changing. Digits =
has a huge amount of RAM, and a CPU from what is traditionally a smartphone=
 chipmaker; this is a far cry from the CPU-centric architectures that under=
gird traditional computing. This is also an area where Apple is well-placed=
, thanks to their unified memory architecture, which means there is lots of=
 RAM available to the GPU.
* Third, the beauty of the Nvidia model is that while the chip in this syst=
em is about 1/40th as powerful as the GB200, it=E2=80=99s still the same ar=
chitecture that runs the same software. Indeed, it=E2=80=99s the same chip =
as the new gaming cards (but, unlike them, is not starved for RAM).

This is how Nvidia can change, and yet be the same. Those old keynotes with=
 a million demos =E2=80=94 the spaghetti against the wall =E2=80=94 was mad=
e possible because it was just new software written for the same architectu=
re. Now that Nvidia has become the proverbial spaghetti monster the approac=
h that makes it possible is identical.

